[1;34m## [0m[1;34mOverview[0m

[1;35m### [0m[1;35mPhilosophy[0m

Markdown is intended to be as easy-to-read and easy-to-write
as is feasible.

Readability, however, is emphasized above all else. A
Markdown-formatted document should be publishable as-is, as
plain text, without looking like it's been marked up with
tags or formatting instructions. While Markdown's syntax has
been influenced by several existing text-to-HTML filters --
including [4m[1;34mSetext[0m
([90mhttp://docutils.sourceforge.net/mirror/setext.html[0m), [4m[1;34matx[0m
([90mhttp://www.aaronsw.com/2002/atx/[0m), [4m[1;34mTextile[0m
([90mhttp://textism.com/tools/textile/[0m), [4m[1;34mreStructuredText[0m
([90mhttp://docutils.sourceforge.net/rst.html[0m), [4m[1;34mGrutatext[0m
([90mhttp://www.triptico.com/software/grutatxt.html[0m), and [4m[1;34mEtText[0m
([90mhttp://ettext.taint.org/doc/[0m) -- the single biggest source
of inspiration for Markdown's syntax is the format of plain
text email.

