[1;35m### [0m[1;35mCode Blocks[0m

Pre-formatted code blocks are used for writing about
programming or markup source code. Rather than forming
normal paragraphs, the lines of a code block are interpreted
literally. Markdown wraps a code block in both [35m<pre>[0m and
[35m<code>[0m tags.

To produce a code block in Markdown, simply indent every
line of the block by at least 4 spaces or 1 tab.

This is a normal paragraph:

[32mThis is a code block.[0m

Here is an example of AppleScript:

[32mtell application "Foo"[0m
[32m    beep[0m
[32mend tell[0m

A code block continues until it reaches a line that is not
indented (or the end of the article).

Within a code block, ampersands ([35m&[0m) and angle brackets ([35m<[0m
and [35m>[0m) are automatically converted into HTML entities. This
makes it very easy to include example HTML source code using
Markdown -- just paste it and indent it, and Markdown will
handle the hassle of encoding the ampersands and angle
brackets. For example, this:

[32m<div class="footer">[0m
[32m    &copy; 2004 Foo Corporation[0m
[32m</div>[0m

Regular Markdown syntax is not processed within code blocks.
E.g., asterisks are just literal asterisks within a code
block. This means it's also easy to use Markdown to write
about Markdown's own syntax.

[32mtell application "Foo"[0m
[32m    beep[0m
[32mend tell[0m

